{"title_page": "Crispina", "text_new": "{{for|the wife of Roman Emperor Commodus|Bruttia Crispina}}\n{{Infobox saint\n|name=Saint Crispina\n|birth_date=3rd century\n|death_date={{death date|304|12|5|mf=y}}\n|feast_day=December 5\n|venerated_in=[[Roman Catholicism]]\n|image=\n|imagesize=\n|caption=\n|birth_place=\n|death_place=[[Theveste]] in [[Numidia]]\n|titles=\n|beatified_date=\n|beatified_place=\n|beatified_by=\n|canonized_date=\n|canonized_place=\n|canonized_by=\n|attributes=\n|patronage=\n|major_shrine=\n|suppressed_date=\n|issues=\n|prayer=\n|prayer_attrib=\n}}\n\n'''Saint Crispina''' (died  December 5, 304) was a [[martyr]] of [[Africa]] who suffered during the [[Diocletian]] persecution.  She was born at [[Thagara]] (Thacora, Tagora) (Thagora was a town in the Roman province of [[Numidia]], located in Taoura, [[Algeria]]. The Tabula Peutingeriana calls it Thacora) in [[North Africa]].  She died by [[Decapitation|beheading]] at [[Theveste]], in [[Numidia]].\n\nCrispina belonged to a distinguished family and was a wealthy [[matron]] with children. At the time of the persecution she was brought before the [[proconsul]] [[Gaius Annius Anullinus|Annius Anullinus]]; on being ordered to sacrifice to the gods she declared she honored only one [[God]]. When threatened with death, Crispina replied: \u201cI care not for the present life, and am only anxious for the life of my soul. I fear eternal torments only.\u201d <ref name=\"Schiavo\">{{cite book|last=Schiavo|first=Anthony|title=I Am A Christian: Authentic Accounts of Christian Martyrdom and Persecution from the Ancient Sources|date=2018|publisher=Arx Publishing|isbn=9781935228189}}</ref> \n\nHer head was shaved at the command of the judge, and she was exposed to public mockery, but she remained steadfast in her faith and was not moved even by the tears of her children. When condemned to death, she thanked God and offered her head with joy for execution.\n\nThe ''Acts'' of her [[martyrdom]], written not long after the event, form a valuable historical document of the period of the persecution. The day of St. Crispina's death was observed in the time of [[Augustine of Hippo]]; in his sermons Augustine repeatedly mentions her name, as well known in Africa and worthy to be held in the same veneration as the names of [[Saint Agnes]] and [[Thecla|St. Thecla]]. In his Sermon on Psalm 120, Augustine says: \"The persecutors turned their rage against Crispina, whose birthday we celebrate today. They unleashed their savagery against a rich woman delicately nurtured; but she was strong, because the Lord was for her a better defense than the hand of her right hand, and He was guarding her. Is there anyone in Africa who does not know about these events, brothers and sisters? Scarcely, for she was extremely famous, of noble stock and very wealthy.\" <ref name=\"Boulding\">{{cite book|last=Boulding|first=Maria|title=Exposition of the Psalms 99-120|date=2003|publisher=New City Press|isbn=9781565481961}}</ref>{{rp|510}}\n\n[[Thierry Ruinart]] in his collection of the [[Acts of the martyrs]] gives the account of her examination. [[Alphonsus Liguori]] provided a version of these acts in his ''Victories of the Martyrs''.\n\n\n\n\nFor more information join our whatsapp group\n\nWhataappgrouponline.com\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{in lang|en}} [http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/04490b.htm Crispina] at the [[Catholic Encyclopedia]]\n* Liguori, Alphonsus. ''Victories of the Martyrs.'', 1776. \n* Ruinart, Theirry. ''Acta Primorum Martyrum Sincera'', 1689.\n* Schiavo, Anthony P. ''[http://www.arxpub.com/literary/i_am_a_christian.html I Am A Christian: Authentic Accounts of Christian Martyrdom and Persecution from the Ancient Sources],'' Merchantville, NJ: Arx Publishing, 2018. (Includes an English translation of the Passion of Saint Crispina as recounted by [[Alphonsus Liguori]] based on the ancient ''Acts'' of Saint Crispina): {{ISBN|978-1-935228-18-9}}\n\n===Videography===\n*''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hPs1tsy147I The Passion of Saint Crispina, Roman North African Martyr of AD 304]'' (2018) \u2013 Excerpt.\n\n{{Catholic}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:304 deaths]]\n[[Category:3rd-century births]]\n[[Category:3rd-century Christian martyrs]]\n[[Category:3rd-century Romans]]\n[[Category:4th-century Roman women]]\n[[Category:Executed women]]\n[[Category:Numidian saints]]\n[[Category:People executed by decapitation]]\n[[Category:People executed for apostasy]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the wife of Roman Emperor Commodus|Bruttia Crispina}}\n{{Infobox saint\n|name=Saint Crispina\n|birth_date=3rd century\n|death_date={{death date|304|12|5|mf=y}}\n|feast_day=December 5\n|venerated_in=[[Roman Catholicism]]\n|image=\n|imagesize=\n|caption=\n|birth_place=\n|death_place=[[Theveste]] in [[Numidia]]\n|titles=\n|beatified_date=\n|beatified_place=\n|beatified_by=\n|canonized_date=\n|canonized_place=\n|canonized_by=\n|attributes=\n|patronage=\n|major_shrine=\n|suppressed_date=\n|issues=\n|prayer=\n|prayer_attrib=\n}}\n\n'''Saint Crispina''' (died  December 5, 304) was a [[martyr]] of [[Africa]] who suffered during the [[Diocletian]] persecution.  She was born at [[Thagara]] (Thacora, Tagora) (Thagora was a town in the Roman province of [[Numidia]], located in Taoura, [[Algeria]]. The Tabula Peutingeriana calls it Thacora) in [[North Africa]].  She died by [[Decapitation|beheading]] at [[Theveste]], in [[Numidia]].\n\nCrispina belonged to a distinguished family and was a wealthy [[matron]] with children. At the time of the persecution she was brought before the [[proconsul]] [[Gaius Annius Anullinus|Annius Anullinus]]; on being ordered to sacrifice to the gods she declared she honored only one [[God]]. When threatened with death, Crispina replied: \u201cI care not for the present life, and am only anxious for the life of my soul. I fear eternal torments only.\u201d <ref name=\"Schiavo\">{{cite book|last=Schiavo|first=Anthony|title=I Am A Christian: Authentic Accounts of Christian Martyrdom and Persecution from the Ancient Sources|date=2018|publisher=Arx Publishing|isbn=9781935228189}}</ref> \n\nHer head was shaved at the command of the judge, and she was exposed to public mockery, but she remained steadfast in her faith and was not moved even by the tears of her children. When condemned to death, she thanked God and offered her head with joy for execution.\n\nThe ''Acts'' of her [[martyrdom]], written not long after the event, form a valuable historical document of the period of the persecution. The day of St. Crispina's death was observed in the time of [[Augustine of Hippo]]; in his sermons Augustine repeatedly mentions her name, as well known in Africa and worthy to be held in the same veneration as the names of [[Saint Agnes]] and [[Thecla|St. Thecla]]. In his Sermon on Psalm 120, Augustine says: \"The persecutors turned their rage against Crispina, whose birthday we celebrate today. They unleashed their savagery against a rich woman delicately nurtured; but she was strong, because the Lord was for her a better defense than the hand of her right hand, and He was guarding her. Is there anyone in Africa who does not know about these events, brothers and sisters? Scarcely, for she was extremely famous, of noble stock and very wealthy.\" <ref name=\"Boulding\">{{cite book|last=Boulding|first=Maria|title=Exposition of the Psalms 99-120|date=2003|publisher=New City Press|isbn=9781565481961}}</ref>{{rp|510}}\n\n[[Thierry Ruinart]] in his collection of the [[Acts of the martyrs]] gives the account of her examination. [[Alphonsus Liguori]] provided a version of these acts in his ''Victories of the Martyrs''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{in lang|en}} [http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/04490b.htm Crispina] at the [[Catholic Encyclopedia]]\n* Liguori, Alphonsus. ''Victories of the Martyrs.'', 1776. \n* Ruinart, Theirry. ''Acta Primorum Martyrum Sincera'', 1689.\n* Schiavo, Anthony P. ''[http://www.arxpub.com/literary/i_am_a_christian.html I Am A Christian: Authentic Accounts of Christian Martyrdom and Persecution from the Ancient Sources],'' Merchantville, NJ: Arx Publishing, 2018. (Includes an English translation of the Passion of Saint Crispina as recounted by [[Alphonsus Liguori]] based on the ancient ''Acts'' of Saint Crispina): {{ISBN|978-1-935228-18-9}}\n\n===Videography===\n*''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hPs1tsy147I The Passion of Saint Crispina, Roman North African Martyr of AD 304]'' (2018) \u2013 Excerpt.\n\n{{Catholic}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:304 deaths]]\n[[Category:3rd-century births]]\n[[Category:3rd-century Christian martyrs]]\n[[Category:3rd-century Romans]]\n[[Category:4th-century Roman women]]\n[[Category:Executed women]]\n[[Category:Numidian saints]]\n[[Category:People executed by decapitation]]\n[[Category:People executed for apostasy]]\n", "name_user": "WhatsApp Group link9521", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(WhatsApp gorup link)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crispina"}
{"title_page": "Lucien Szpiro", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|French mathematician}}\n{{ Infobox scientist\n| name              = Lucien Szpiro\n| image             = LucienSzpiro.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = Szpiro at the [[Mathematical Research Institute of Oberwolfach]]\n| birth_date        = {{birth date|df=yes|1941|12|23}}\n| birth_place       = [[Paris]], France\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2020|4|18|1941|12|23}}\n| death_place       = Paris, France\n| nationality       = French\n| fields            = [[Mathematics]]\n| workplaces        = [[City University of New York]]{{br}}[[French National Centre for Scientific Research|CNRS]]\n| alma_mater        = [[Paris-Sud University]]\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Pierre Samuel]]\n| influences        = [[Maurice Auslander]]{{br}}[[Claude Chevalley]]{{br}}[[Alexander Grothendieck]]\n| doctoral_students = [[Emmanuel Ullmo]]<br>[[Shou-Wu Zhang]]\n| known_for         = [[Szpiro's conjecture]]\n| awards            = [[French Academy of Sciences|Prix Doistau\u2013Blutel]] (1987){{br}}Fellow of the [[American Mathematical Society]] (2012){{br}}[[Member of the Academia Europaea]]\n}}\n\n'''Lucien Szpiro''' (23 December 1941&nbsp;\u2013 18 April 2020) was a French [[mathematician]] known for his work in [[number theory]], [[arithmetic geometry]], and [[commutative algebra]]. He formulated [[Szpiro's conjecture]] and was a Distinguished Professor at the [[Graduate Center, CUNY|CUNY Graduate Center]] and an emeritus {{ill|Director of Research|fr|Directeur de recherche au CNRS}} at the [[French National Centre for Scientific Research|CNRS]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nLucien Szpiro was born on 23 December 1941 in [[Paris]], France.<ref name=CV>{{cite web |url=https://www.gc.cuny.edu/CUNY_GC/media/CUNY-Graduate-Center/PDF/Programs/Math/CVFall2010.pdf |title=Curriculum Vitae |date=2010 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> Szpiro attended [[Paris-Sud University]] where he earned his [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] under [[Pierre Samuel]].<ref name=CV/> His doctoral work was heavily influenced by the seminars of [[Maurice Auslander]], [[Claude Chevalley]], and [[Alexander Grothendieck]].<ref name=CV/> He earned his [[Habilitation#France|Doctorat d'\u00c9tat]] (DrE) in 1971.<ref name=CV/>\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1963 to 1965, Szpiro worked as an assistant high school teacher in Paris.<ref name=CV/><ref name=ae/> From 1965 to 1969, he was an assistant professor (''ma\u00eetre assistant'') at the [[University of Paris]].<ref name=CV/><ref name=ae/> From 1969 to 1999, Szpiro worked at the CNRS, initially as an [[Academic_ranks_in_France#Temporary_positions|attach\u00e9]] at [[Paris Diderot University]] before rising to the rank of a distinguished professor (''Directeur de Recherche de Classe Exceptionnelle'') at [[Paris-Sud University]].<ref name=ae/> In 1999, he became a ''Directeur de Recherche \u00e9m\u00e9rite'' at the CNRS and moved to the CUNY Graduate Center as a Distinguished Professor.<ref name=CV/><ref name=ae/><ref name=GS>{{cite web |url=https://www.gc.cuny.edu/Faculty/Core-Bios/Lucien-Szpiro |website=[[Graduate Center, CUNY]] |title=Lucien Szpiro |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> He also held visiting positions at several institutions including [[Columbia University]] and the [[Institute for Advanced Study]].<ref name=ae/><ref name=\"IAS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ias.edu/scholars/lucien-szpiro |title=Lucien Szpiro |website=[[Institute for Advanced Study]] |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSzpiro was the editor-in-chief of ''[[Ast\u00e9risque]]'' from 1991 to 1993 and an editor of the ''[[Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Math\u00e9matique de France]]'' from 1984 to 1990.<ref name=CV/> He was also head of the commission that oversaw the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 math\u00e9matique de France]] libraries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enssib.fr/bibliotheque-numerique/documents/62615-reseau-de-bibliotheques-specialisees-le-reseau-des-bibliotheques-de-mathematiquesmemoire-d-etude-un.pdf?telecharger=1 |title=Un r\u00e9seau de biblith\u00e8ques sp\u00e9cialis\u00e9es: le r\u00e9seau des biblioth\u00e8ques de mathematiques |website=[[\u00c9cole Nationale Sup\u00e9rieure des Sciences de l'Information et des Biblioth\u00e8ques]] |date=1992 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |lang=fr |quote=Lucien Szpiro, responsable de la commission des bibliotheques de la SMF, estime que le cout de l'operation serait de 100 000 francs par an pour un reseau ne contenant que des listes de livres et de preprints.}}</ref>\n\nSzpiro advised 17 doctoral students, including [[Emmanuel Ullmo]] and [[Shou-Wu Zhang]].<ref name=CV/><ref name=mgp>{{MathGenealogy |id=37670 }}</ref>\n\n==Research==\nSzpiro was one of the pioneers of [[Arakelov theory]] as a tool of modern [[Diophantine geometry]].<ref name=GS/> After moving to the CUNY Graduate Center in 1999, he began working on new research in [[algebraic dynamics]].<ref name=GS/>\n\nIn 1981, Szpiro formulated a conjecture (now known as Szpiro's conjecture) relating the discriminant of an [[elliptic curve]] with its [[conductor of an elliptic curve|conductor]].<ref name=\"lang\">{{cite book|first=Serge |last=Lang |authorlink=Serge Lang |title=Survey of Diophantine geometry |publisher=[[Springer-Verlag]] |location=Berlin |year=1997 |isbn=3-540-61223-8 | zbl=0869.11051 | page=51 }}</ref> His conjecture inspired the [[abc conjecture|''abc'' conjecture]],<ref name=\"Fesenko\">{{cite journal|title=Arithmetic deformation theory via arithmetic fundamental groups and nonarchimedean theta functions, notes on the work of Shinichi Mochizuki|journal= European Journal of Mathematics|first=Ivan|last=Fesenko|volume=1 |issue=3| pages=405\u2013440 | year=2015 |url=https://www.maths.nottingham.ac.uk/personal/ibf/notesoniut.pdf |doi=10.1007/s40879-015-0066-0}}.</ref> which was later shown to be equivalent to a modified form of Szpiro's conjecture in 1988.<ref name=\"Oesterle-1988\">{{cite journal| last1=Oesterl\u00e9 | first1=Joseph | authorlink=Joseph Oesterl\u00e9 | title=Nouvelles approches du \"th\u00e9or\u00e8me\" de Fermat | url= http://www.numdam.org/item?id=SB_1987-1988__30__165_0 | series=S\u00e9minaire Bourbaki exp 694 |mr=992208 | year=1988 | journal=Ast\u00e9risque | issn=0303-1179 | issue=161 | pages=165\u2013186}}</ref> Szpiro's conjecture and its equivalent forms have been described as \"the most important unsolved problem in [[Diophantine analysis]]\" by [[Dorian Goldfeld]],<ref name=\"Goldfeld-1996\">{{cite journal |last=Goldfeld |first=Dorian | authorlink=Dorian M. Goldfeld |year=1996 |title=Beyond the last theorem |journal=[[Math Horizons]] |volume=4 |issue=September |pages=26\u201334 |jstor= 25678079 |ref=harv |doi=10.1080/10724117.1996.11974985 }}</ref> in part to its large number of consequences in number theory including [[Roth's theorem]], the [[Faltings's theorem|Mordell conjecture]], the [[Fermat\u2013Catalan conjecture]], and [[Brocard's problem]].<ref>{{cite journal | first1=Enrico | last=Bombieri | title=Roth's theorem and the abc-conjecture | journal=Preprint | year=1994 | publisher=ETH Z\u00fcrich | ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Elkies |first=N. D. |authorlink=Noam Elkies |title=ABC implies Mordell |journal= International Mathematics Research Notices|volume=1991 |year=1991 |pages=99\u2013109 |doi=10.1155/S1073792891000144 |issue=7 |ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Pomerance |first=Carl |authorlink=Carl Pomerance |chapter=Computational Number Theory |title=The Princeton Companion to Mathematics |location= |publisher=Princeton University Press |year=2008 |pages=361\u2013362 |ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |first=Andrzej |last=D\u0105browski |title=On the diophantine equation ''x''! + ''A'' = ''y''<sup>2</sup> | journal=Nieuw Archief voor Wiskunde, IV. |volume=14 |pages=321\u2013324 |year=1996 | zbl=0876.11015 | ref=harv }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1987, Szpiro received the Doistau\u2013Blutel Prize from the [[French Academy of Sciences]] \"for his work in Commutative Algebra and Algebraic Geometry and for his contribution to G. Faltings\u2019 proof of the [[Mordell conjecture]].\"<ref name=GS/> In 2012 he became a fellow of the [[American Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.ams.org/profession/fellows-list List of Fellows of the American Mathematical Society], retrieved 5 August 2013.</ref> He was a [[Member of the Academia Europaea]].<ref name=ae>{{cite web |url=https://www.ae-info.org/ae/Member/Szpiro_Lucien |website=[[Academia Europaea]] |title=Lucien Szpiro |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nSzpiro died on 18 April 2020 in Paris, France from [[cardiac arrest]].<ref name=NEW>{{Cite web|url=https://www.math.columbia.edu/~woit/wordpress/?p=11717|title=Lucien Szpiro 1941-2020 &#124; Not Even Wrong}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n*{{cite journal |last=Pesenti |first=Jerome |last2=Szpiro |first2=Lucien |year=2000 |title=In\u00e9galit\u00e9 du discriminant pour les pinceaux elliptiques \u00e0 r\u00e9ductions quelconques |url=http://www.journals.cambridge.org/abstract_S0010437X00000014 |journal=[[Compositio Mathematica]] |volume=120 |issue=1 |pages=83\u2013117 |doi=10.1023/A:1001736823128}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Peskine |first=Christian |last2=Szpiro |first2=Lucien |year=1973 |title=Dimension projective finie et cohomologie locale: Applications \u00e0 la d\u00e9monstration de conjectures de M. Auslander, H. Bass et A. Grothendieck |url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/BF02685877 |journal=[[Publications math\u00e9matiques de l'IH\u00c9S]] |language=fr |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=47\u2013119 |doi=10.1007/BF02685877 |issn=0073-8301}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Peskine |first=Christian |last2=Szpiro |first2=Lucien |year=1974 |title=Liaison des vari\u00e9t\u00e9s alg\u00e9briques I |url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/BF01425554 |journal=[[Inventiones Mathematicae]] |language=fr |volume=26 |issue=4 |pages=271\u2013302 |doi=10.1007/BF01425554 |issn=0020-9910}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Szpiro |first1=Lucien |authorlink1=Lucien Szpiro |last2=Ullmo |first2=Emmanuel |authorlink2=Emmanuel Ullmo |last3=Zhang |first3=Shou-Wu |authorlink3=Shou-Wu Zhang |title=Equir\u00e9partition des petits points |language=fr |journal=Inventiones Mathematicae |volume=127 |issue=2 |year=1997 |pages=337\u2013347|doi=10.1007/s002220050123 |bibcode=1997InMat.127..337S }}\n*{{cite journal |url=http://www.numdam.org/item/?id=AST_1979__64__169_0 |title=Sur le th\u00e9or\u00e8me de rigidit\u00e9 de Parsin et Arakelov |last=Szpiro |first=Lucien |journal=[[Ast\u00e9risque]] |volume=64 |year=1979 |pages=169\u2013202 |series=Journ\u00e9es de g\u00e9om\u00e9trie alg\u00e9brique de Rennes - (Juillet 1978) (II) : Groupes formels, repr\u00e9sentations galoisiennes et cohomologie des vari\u00e9t\u00e9s de caract\u00e9ristique positive |MR=563470}}\n*{{cite journal |first=Lucien |last=Szpiro |title=Seminaire sur les pinceaux des courbes de genre au moins deux |journal=Ast\u00e9risque |volume=86 |issue=3 |year=1981 | zbl=0463.00009 | pages=44\u201378 }}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Ribet |editor-first=Kenneth A. |editor-link=Ken Ribet |first=Lucien |last=Szpiro |title=Current Trends in Arithmetical Algebraic Geometry |chapter=Pr\u00e9sentation de la th\u00e9orie d'Arakelov |series=Contemporary Mathematics |volume=67 |year=1987 | zbl=0634.14012 | pages=279\u2013293 |doi=10.1090/conm/067/902599}}\n*Szpiro, Lucien. [http://www.numdam.org/numdam-bin/fitem?id=SB_1983-1984__26__83_0 ''Conjecture de Mordell''], [[S\u00e9minaire Nicolas Bourbaki]] 1983/4.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web| url=http://math.gc.cuny.edu/faculty/szpiro/People_Faculty_Szpiro.html|title= Website at CUNY}}\n*{{MathGenealogy |id=37670 }}\n*[https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=0%2C11&q=author%3Alucien+author%3Aszpiro Search on author Lucien Szpiro] from [[Google Scholar]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Szpiro, Lucien}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:French mathematicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century mathematicians]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:City University of New York faculty]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Mathematical Society]]\n[[Category:Members of Academia Europaea]]\n[[Category:Paris-Sud 11 University faculty]]\n[[Category:Arithmetic geometers]]\n[[Category:Institute for Advanced Study visiting scholars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|French mathematician}}\n{{ Infobox scientist\n| name              = Lucien Szpiro\n| image             = LucienSzpiro.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = Szpiro at the [[Mathematical Research Institute of Oberwolfach]]\n| birth_date        = {{birth date|df=yes|1941|12|23}}\n| birth_place       = [[Paris]], France\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2020|4|18|1941|12|23}}\n| death_place       = Paris, France\n| nationality       = French\n| fields            = [[Mathematics]]\n| workplaces        = [[City University of New York]]{{br}}[[French National Centre for Scientific Research|CNRS]]\n| alma_mater        = [[Paris-Sud University]]\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Pierre Samuel]]\n| influences        = [[Maurice Auslander]]{{br}}[[Claude Chevalley]]{{br}}[[Alexander Grothendieck]]\n| doctoral_students = [[Emmanuel Ullmo]]<br>[[Shou-Wu Zhang]]\n| known_for         = [[Szpiro's conjecture]]\n| awards            = [[French Academy of Sciences|Prix Doistau\u2013Blutel]] (1987){{br}}Fellow of the [[American Mathematical Society]] (2012){{br}}[[Member of the Academia Europaea]]\n}}\n\n'''Lucien Szpiro''' (23 December 1941 \u2013 18 April 2020) was a French [[mathematician]], known for his work in [[number theory]], [[arithmetic geometry]], and [[commutative algebra]]. He formulated [[Szpiro's conjecture]] and was a Distinguished Professor at the [[Graduate Center, CUNY|CUNY Graduate Center]] and an emeritus {{ill|Director of Research|fr|Directeur de recherche au CNRS}} at the [[French National Centre for Scientific Research|CNRS]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nLucien Szpiro was born on 23 December 1941 in [[Paris]], France.<ref name=CV>{{cite web |url=https://www.gc.cuny.edu/CUNY_GC/media/CUNY-Graduate-Center/PDF/Programs/Math/CVFall2010.pdf |title=Curriculum Vitae |date=2010 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> Szpiro attended [[Paris-Sud University]] where he earned his [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] under [[Pierre Samuel]].<ref name=CV/> His doctoral work was heavily influenced by the seminars of [[Maurice Auslander]], [[Claude Chevalley]], and [[Alexander Grothendieck]].<ref name=CV/> He earned his [[Habilitation#France|Doctorat d'\u00c9tat]] (DrE) in 1971.<ref name=CV/>\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1963 to 1965, Szpiro worked as an assistant high school teacher in Paris.<ref name=CV/><ref name=ae/> From 1965 to 1969, he was an assistant professor (''ma\u00eetre assistant'') at the [[University of Paris]].<ref name=CV/><ref name=ae/> From 1969 to 1999, Szpiro worked at the CNRS, initially as an [[Academic_ranks_in_France#Temporary_positions|attach\u00e9]] at [[Paris Diderot University]] before rising to the rank of a distinguished professor (''Directeur de Recherche de Classe Exceptionnelle'') at [[Paris-Sud University]].<ref name=ae/> In 1999, he became a ''Directeur de Recherche \u00e9m\u00e9rite'' at the CNRS and moved to the CUNY Graduate Center as a Distinguished Professor.<ref name=CV/><ref name=ae/><ref name=GS>{{cite web |url=https://www.gc.cuny.edu/Faculty/Core-Bios/Lucien-Szpiro |website=[[Graduate Center, CUNY]] |title=Lucien Szpiro |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> He also held visiting positions at several institutions including [[Columbia University]] and the [[Institute for Advanced Study]].<ref name=ae/><ref name=\"IAS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ias.edu/scholars/lucien-szpiro |title=Lucien Szpiro |website=[[Institute for Advanced Study]] |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSzpiro was the editor-in-chief of ''[[Ast\u00e9risque]]'' from 1991 to 1993 and an editor of the ''[[Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Math\u00e9matique de France]]'' from 1984 to 1990.<ref name=CV/> He was also head of the commission that oversaw the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 math\u00e9matique de France]] libraries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enssib.fr/bibliotheque-numerique/documents/62615-reseau-de-bibliotheques-specialisees-le-reseau-des-bibliotheques-de-mathematiquesmemoire-d-etude-un.pdf?telecharger=1 |title=Un r\u00e9seau de biblith\u00e8ques sp\u00e9cialis\u00e9es: le r\u00e9seau des biblioth\u00e8ques de mathematiques |website=[[\u00c9cole Nationale Sup\u00e9rieure des Sciences de l'Information et des Biblioth\u00e8ques]] |date=1992 |accessdate=19 April 2020 |lang=fr |quote=Lucien Szpiro, responsable de la commission des bibliotheques de la SMF, estime que le cout de l'operation serait de 100 000 francs par an pour un reseau ne contenant que des listes de livres et de preprints.}}</ref>\n\nSzpiro advised 17 doctoral students, including [[Emmanuel Ullmo]] and [[Shou-Wu Zhang]].<ref name=CV/><ref name=mgp>{{MathGenealogy |id=37670 }}</ref>\n\n==Research==\nSzpiro was one of the pioneers of [[Arakelov theory]] as a tool of modern [[Diophantine geometry]].<ref name=GS/> After moving to the CUNY Graduate Center in 1999, he began working on new research in [[algebraic dynamics]].<ref name=GS/>\n\nIn 1981, Szpiro formulated a conjecture (now known as Szpiro's conjecture) relating the discriminant of an [[elliptic curve]] with its [[conductor of an elliptic curve|conductor]].<ref name=\"lang\">{{cite book|first=Serge |last=Lang |authorlink=Serge Lang |title=Survey of Diophantine geometry |publisher=[[Springer-Verlag]] |location=Berlin |year=1997 |isbn=3-540-61223-8 | zbl=0869.11051 | page=51 }}</ref> His conjecture inspired the [[abc conjecture|''abc'' conjecture]],<ref name=\"Fesenko\">{{cite journal|title=Arithmetic deformation theory via arithmetic fundamental groups and nonarchimedean theta functions, notes on the work of Shinichi Mochizuki|journal= European Journal of Mathematics|first=Ivan|last=Fesenko|volume=1 |issue=3| pages=405\u2013440 | year=2015 |url=https://www.maths.nottingham.ac.uk/personal/ibf/notesoniut.pdf |doi=10.1007/s40879-015-0066-0}}.</ref> which was later shown to be equivalent to a modified form of Szpiro's conjecture in 1988.<ref name=\"Oesterle-1988\">{{cite journal| last1=Oesterl\u00e9 | first1=Joseph | authorlink=Joseph Oesterl\u00e9 | title=Nouvelles approches du \"th\u00e9or\u00e8me\" de Fermat | url= http://www.numdam.org/item?id=SB_1987-1988__30__165_0 | series=S\u00e9minaire Bourbaki exp 694 |mr=992208 | year=1988 | journal=Ast\u00e9risque | issn=0303-1179 | issue=161 | pages=165\u2013186}}</ref> Szpiro's conjecture and its equivalent forms have been described as \"the most important unsolved problem in [[Diophantine analysis]]\" by [[Dorian Goldfeld]],<ref name=\"Goldfeld-1996\">{{cite journal |last=Goldfeld |first=Dorian | authorlink=Dorian M. Goldfeld |year=1996 |title=Beyond the last theorem |journal=[[Math Horizons]] |volume=4 |issue=September |pages=26\u201334 |jstor= 25678079 |ref=harv |doi=10.1080/10724117.1996.11974985 }}</ref> in part to its large number of consequences in number theory including [[Roth's theorem]], the [[Faltings's theorem|Mordell conjecture]], the [[Fermat\u2013Catalan conjecture]], and [[Brocard's problem]].<ref>{{cite journal | first1=Enrico | last=Bombieri | title=Roth's theorem and the abc-conjecture | journal=Preprint | year=1994 | publisher=ETH Z\u00fcrich | ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Elkies |first=N. D. |authorlink=Noam Elkies |title=ABC implies Mordell |journal=  International Mathematics Research Notices|volume=1991 |year=1991 |pages=99\u2013109 |doi=10.1155/S1073792891000144 |issue=7 |ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Pomerance |first=Carl |authorlink=Carl Pomerance |chapter=Computational Number Theory |title=The Princeton Companion to Mathematics |location= |publisher=Princeton University Press |year=2008 |pages=361\u2013362 |ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |first=Andrzej |last=D\u0105browski |title=On the diophantine equation ''x''! + ''A'' = ''y''<sup>2</sup> | journal=Nieuw Archief voor Wiskunde, IV. |volume=14 |pages=321\u2013324 |year=1996 | zbl=0876.11015 | ref=harv }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1987, Szpiro received the Doistau\u2013Blutel Prize from the [[French Academy of Sciences]] \"for his work in Commutative Algebra and Algebraic Geometry and for his contribution to G. Faltings\u2019 proof of the [[Mordell conjecture]].\"<ref name=GS/> In 2012 he became a fellow of the [[American Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.ams.org/profession/fellows-list List of Fellows of the American Mathematical Society], retrieved 5 August 2013.</ref> He was a [[Member of the Academia Europaea]].<ref name=ae>{{cite web |url=https://www.ae-info.org/ae/Member/Szpiro_Lucien |website=[[Academia Europaea]] |title=Lucien Szpiro |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nSzpiro died on 18 April 2020 in Paris, France from [[cardiac arrest]].<ref name=NEW>{{Cite web|url=https://www.math.columbia.edu/~woit/wordpress/?p=11717|title=Lucien Szpiro 1941-2020 &#124; Not Even Wrong}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n*{{cite journal |last=Pesenti |first=Jerome |last2=Szpiro |first2=Lucien |year=2000 |title=In\u00e9galit\u00e9 du discriminant pour les pinceaux elliptiques \u00e0 r\u00e9ductions quelconques |url=http://www.journals.cambridge.org/abstract_S0010437X00000014 |journal=[[Compositio Mathematica]] |volume=120 |issue=1 |pages=83\u2013117 |doi=10.1023/A:1001736823128}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Peskine |first=Christian |last2=Szpiro |first2=Lucien |year=1973 |title=Dimension projective finie et cohomologie locale: Applications \u00e0 la d\u00e9monstration de conjectures de M. Auslander, H. Bass et A. Grothendieck |url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/BF02685877 |journal=[[Publications math\u00e9matiques de l'IH\u00c9S]] |language=fr |volume=42 |issue=1 |pages=47\u2013119 |doi=10.1007/BF02685877 |issn=0073-8301}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Peskine |first=Christian |last2=Szpiro |first2=Lucien |year=1974 |title=Liaison des vari\u00e9t\u00e9s alg\u00e9briques I |url=http://link.springer.com/10.1007/BF01425554 |journal=[[Inventiones Mathematicae]] |language=fr |volume=26 |issue=4 |pages=271\u2013302 |doi=10.1007/BF01425554 |issn=0020-9910}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Szpiro |first1=Lucien |authorlink1=Lucien Szpiro |last2=Ullmo |first2=Emmanuel |authorlink2=Emmanuel Ullmo |last3=Zhang |first3=Shou-Wu |authorlink3=Shou-Wu Zhang |title=Equir\u00e9partition des petits points |language=fr |journal=Inventiones Mathematicae |volume=127 |issue=2 |year=1997 |pages=337\u2013347|doi=10.1007/s002220050123 |bibcode=1997InMat.127..337S }}\n*{{cite journal |url=http://www.numdam.org/item/?id=AST_1979__64__169_0 |title=Sur le th\u00e9or\u00e8me de rigidit\u00e9 de Parsin et Arakelov |last=Szpiro |first=Lucien |journal=[[Ast\u00e9risque]] |volume=64 |year=1979 |pages=169\u2013202 |series=Journ\u00e9es de g\u00e9om\u00e9trie alg\u00e9brique de Rennes - (Juillet 1978) (II) : Groupes formels, repr\u00e9sentations galoisiennes et cohomologie des vari\u00e9t\u00e9s de caract\u00e9ristique positive |MR=563470}}\n*{{cite journal |first=Lucien |last=Szpiro |title=Seminaire sur les pinceaux des courbes de genre au moins deux |journal=Ast\u00e9risque |volume=86 |issue=3 |year=1981 | zbl=0463.00009 | pages=44\u201378 }}\n*{{cite book |editor-last=Ribet |editor-first=Kenneth A. |editor-link=Ken Ribet |first=Lucien |last=Szpiro |title=Current Trends in Arithmetical Algebraic Geometry |chapter=Pr\u00e9sentation de la th\u00e9orie d'Arakelov |series=Contemporary Mathematics |volume=67 |year=1987 | zbl=0634.14012 | pages=279\u2013293 |doi=10.1090/conm/067/902599}}\n*Szpiro, Lucien. [http://www.numdam.org/numdam-bin/fitem?id=SB_1983-1984__26__83_0 ''Conjecture de Mordell''], [[S\u00e9minaire Nicolas Bourbaki]] 1983/4.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web| url=http://math.gc.cuny.edu/faculty/szpiro/People_Faculty_Szpiro.html|title= Website at CUNY}}\n*{{MathGenealogy |id=37670 }}\n*[https://scholar.google.com/scholar?hl=en&as_sdt=0%2C11&q=author%3Alucien+author%3Aszpiro Search on author Lucien Szpiro] from [[Google Scholar]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Szpiro, Lucien}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:French mathematicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century mathematicians]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:City University of New York faculty]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Mathematical Society]]\n[[Category:Members of Academia Europaea]]\n[[Category:Paris-Sud 11 University faculty]]\n[[Category:Arithmetic geometers]]\n[[Category:Institute for Advanced Study visiting scholars]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucien_Szpiro"}
{"title_page": "Papyrus 48", "text_new": "{{New Testament manuscript infobox\n| form   = Papyrus\n| number = '''<math>\\mathfrak{P}</math><sup>48</sup>'''\n| image  = P048-Act-23 11-17-III.jpg\n| isize  = \n| caption= \n| name   = \n| sign   = \n| text   = [[Acts of the Apostles]] 23 \u2020\n| script = [[Greek language|Greek]]\n| date   = 3rd century\n| found  = [[Egypt]]\n| now at = [[Laurentian Library]]\n| cite   = G. Vitelli and S. G. Mercati, PGLSI X, (1932), pp. 112-118.\n| size   = 16 x 25 cm\n| type   = [[Western text-type]]\n| cat    = IV\n| hand   = \n| note   = \n}}\n\n'''Papyrus 48''' (Gregory-Aland), signed by '''<math>\\mathfrak{P}</math><sup>48</sup>''', is an early copy of a part of the [[New Testament]] in [[Greek language|Greek]]. It is a [[papyrus]] [[manuscript]] of the [[Acts of the Apostles]], it contains portions of Acts 23:11-29.\nThe manuscript [[Palaeography|paleographically]] has been assigned to the 3rd century.\n\nAlthough the text of this codex is extremely small, the Greek text of this codex has been called a representative of the [[Western text-type]]. [[Kurt Aland|Aland]] placed it in [[Categories of New Testament manuscripts#Category IV|Category IV]].<ref name = Aland>{{Cite book\n |last=Aland\n |first=Kurt\n |authorlink=Kurt Aland\n | last2 = Aland\n | first2 = Barbara\n | authorlink2 = Barbara Aland\n | others = Erroll F. Rhodes (trans.)\n |title=The Text of the New Testament: An Introduction to the Critical Editions and to the Theory and Practice of Modern Textual Criticism\n |publisher=[[William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company]]\n |year=1995\n |location=Grand Rapids\n |page=99\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2pYDsAhUOxAC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false\n |isbn=978-0-8028-4098-1}}</ref>\n\nIt is currently housed at the [[Laurentian Library]] (PSI 1165) in [[Florence]].<ref name = Aland/><ref name = INTF>{{Cite web|url=http://intf.uni-muenster.de/vmr/NTVMR/ListeHandschriften.php?ObjID=10048|title= Liste Handschriften|publisher=Institute for New Testament Textual Research|accessdate=26 August 2011|location=M\u00fcnster}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of New Testament papyri]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* G. Vitelli and S. G. Mercati, ''Papiri greci e latini della Societ\u00e0 Italiana'' X, (1932), pp.&nbsp;112\u2013118.\n* {{Cite book\n | last = Comfort\n | first = Philip W.\n | authorlink = Philip Comfort\n | author2 = David P. Barrett\n | title = The Text of the Earliest New Testament Greek Manuscripts\n | publisher = Tyndale House Publishers\n | year = 2001\n | location = Wheaton, Illinois\n | pages = 352\u2013354\n | url = \n | isbn = 978-0-8423-5265-9}}\n\n== Images ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110714131742/http://chrles.multiply.com/photos/album/80/Bible_Papyrus_p48#2 Image <math>\\mathfrak{P}</math><sup>48</sup> verso] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110714131742/http://chrles.multiply.com/photos/album/80/Bible_Papyrus_p48#3 Image <math>\\mathfrak{P}</math><sup>48</sup> reverso]\n\n== External links ==\n\n* Robert B. Waltz. [http://www.skypoint.com/members/waltzmn/ManuscriptsPapyri.html#P48 ''NT Manuscripts: Papyri, Papyri <math>\\mathfrak{P}</math><sup>48</sup>''] Encyclopedia of Textual Criticism\n\n{{New Testament papyri}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Papyrus 0048}}\n[[Category:New Testament papyri]]\n[[Category:3rd-century biblical manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Early Greek manuscripts of the New Testament]]\n[[Category:Acts of the Apostles papyri]]\n", "text_old": "{{New Testament manuscript infobox\n| form   = Papyrus\n| number = '''<math>\\mathfrak{P}</math><sup>48</sup>'''\n| image  = P048-Act-23 11-17-III.jpg\n| isize  = \n| caption= \n| name   = \n| sign   = \n| text   = [[Acts of the Apostles]] 23 \u2020\n| script = [[Greek language|Greek]]\n| date   = 3rd century\n| found  = [[Egypt]]\n| now at = [[Laurentian Library]]\n| cite   = G. Vitelli and S. G. Mercati, PGLSI X, (1932), pp. 112-118.\n| size   = 16 x 25 cm\n| type   = [[Western text-type]]\n| cat    = IV\n| hand   = \n| note   = \n}}\n\n'''Papyrus 48''' (Gregory-Aland), signed by '''<math>\\mathfrak{P}</math><sup>48</sup>''', is an early copy of a part of the [[New Testament]] in [[Greek language|Greek]]. It is a [[papyrus]] [[manuscript]] of the [[Acts of the Apostles]], it contains portions of Acts 23:11-29.\nThe manuscript [[Palaeography|paleographically]] has been assigned to the 3rd century.\n\nAlthough the text of this codex is extremely small, the Greek text of this codex has been called a representative of the [[Western text-type]]. [[Kurt Aland|Aland]] placed it in [[Categories of New Testament manuscripts#Category IV|Category IV]].<ref name = Aland>{{Cite book\n |last=Aland\n |first=Kurt\n |authorlink=Kurt Aland\n | last2 = Aland\n | first2 = Barbara\n | authorlink2 = Barbara Aland\n | others = Erroll F. Rhodes (trans.)\n |title=The Text of the New Testament: An Introduction to the Critical Editions and to the Theory and Practice of Modern Textual Criticism\n |publisher=[[William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company]]\n |year=1995\n |location=Grand Rapids\n |page=99\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2pYDsAhUOxAC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false\n |isbn=978-0-8028-4098-1}}</ref>\n\nIt is currently housed at the [[Laurentian Library]] (PSI 1165) in [[Florence]].<ref name = Aland/><ref name = INTF>{{Cite web|url=http://intf.uni-muenster.de/vmr/NTVMR/ListeHandschriften.php?ObjID=10048|title= Liste Handschriften|publisher=Institute for New Testament Textual Research|accessdate=26 August 2011|location=M\u00fcnster}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of New Testament papyri]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* G. Vitelli and S. G. Mercati, ''Papiri greci e latini della Societ\u00e0 Italiana'' X, (1932), pp.&nbsp;112\u2013118.\n* {{Cite book\n | last = Comfort\n | first = Philip W.\n | authorlink = Philip Comfort\n | author2 = David P. Barrett\n | title = The Text of the Earliest New Testament Greek Manuscripts\n | publisher = Tyndale House Publishers\n | year = 2001\n | location = Wheaton, Illinois\n | pages = 352\u2013354\n | url = \n | isbn = 978-0-8423-5265-9}}\n\n== Images ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110714131742/http://chrles.multiply.com/photos/album/80/Bible_Papyrus_p48#2 Image <math>\\mathfrak{P}</math><sup>48</sup> verso] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110714131742/http://chrles.multiply.com/photos/album/80/Bible_Papyrus_p48#3 Image <math>\\mathfrak{P}</math><sup>48</sup> reverso]\n\n== External links ==\n\n* Robert B. Waltz. [http://www.skypoint.com/members/waltzmn/ManuscriptsPapyri.html#P48 ''NT Manuscripts: Papyri, Papyri <math>\\mathfrak{P}</math><sup>48</sup>''] Encyclopedia of Textual Criticism\n\n{{New Testament papyri}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Papyrus 0048}}\n[[Kategorie:Biblische Manuskripte aus dem 3. Jahrhundert]]\n[[Category:New Testament papyri]]\n[[Category:3rd-century biblical manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Early Greek manuscripts of the New Testament]]\n[[Category:Acts of the Apostles papyri]]\n", "name_user": "Jairon Levid Abimael Ca\u00e1l Orozco", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Papyrus_48"}
{"title_page": "Eric Butcher", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n\n| image         = File:Eric Butcher in his studio, photographed by Jonny Back.jpg\n| alt           =\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       = Eric Butcher in his studio\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1970}}\n| birth_place   = Singapore\n| nationality   = [[Great Britain|British]]\n| field         = Painting\n| training      = [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], \n[[Wimbledon College of Art|Wimbledon School of Art]]\n| movement      = [[Abstract art]]\n| works         =\n}}\n\n'''Eric Butcher''' (born 1970) is a contemporary British abstract painter known for his reductive, processed-based approach.\n\nButcher read philosophy at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], graduating in 1994 and completed an MA in Fine Art at [[Wimbledon College of Art|Wimbledon School of Art]] in 2001. He has exhibited extensively in the UK and internationally with shows in Germany, Italy, Australia and the USA.<ref name=\"Underground\">(2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.78. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> He currently shows with Toomey Tourell gallery, San Francisco,<ref>Toomey-Tourell Fine Art [http://toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ \"Eric Butcher\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001153714/http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher |date=2012-10-01 }}</ref> Galerie Robert Drees in Hannover<ref>Galerie Robert Drees [http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher |date=2012-08-23 }}\"Eric Butcher\"</ref> and Patrick Heide Contemporary Art.<ref>Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, Collaborating Artists [https://www.patrickheide.com/index.php/artists/eric-butcher]</ref> \n\nHe has received awards from the [[Arts Council England|Arts Council, England]] and the [[Arts and Humanities Research Council]]. He has also held an Arts Institute at Bournemouth Research Fellowship (now the [[Arts University Bournemouth|AUB]]<ref>[http://aub.ac.uk/about-us/governance/\u201dArts University College Bournemouth\u201d]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref>) and was the Centre for Arts International Research/Liverpool School of Art & Design Multiple Perspectives Fellow 2007.<ref name=\"Underground\" />\n\nButcher was a selected artist in the final Jerwood Drawing Prize in 2017<ref>Jerwood Drawing Prize 2017, published by the Jerwood Charitable Foundation, London {{ISBN|978-1-908331-29-8}} (texts: Anita Taylor, David Dibosa, Helen Legg, Michael Simpson)</ref> (now [[Trinity Buoy Wharf Drawing Prize]]) alongside artists such as [[Barbara Walker (artist)]] and selected by writer/curator, David Dibosa; director of [[Tate Liverpool]], Helen Legg (then director of [[Spike Island Artspace]]); and [[Michael Simpson (painter)]]. In 2020 Butcher exhibited his second solo show, Sweet Heresy<ref>Sweet Heresy | Eric Butcher [https://www.patrickheide.com/exhibitions/sweet-heresy-eric-butcher]</ref>, at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, which coincided with the release of Time Trial, a newly published 160-page hardback catalogue of his recent work.<ref>\u201dTime Trial\u201d, Eric Butcher {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}.</ref>\n\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Early Life and Education==\nEric Butcher was born in Singapore in 1970 to a Dutch mother and British father. Shortly after he was born the family moved to Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia and then settled in the UK in Hampshire, England in 1974.\nAfter leaving school at 16 he spent two formative years studying art at [[Basingstoke College of Technology]], after which he undertook A Levels at evening classes and eventually found his way to [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], reading philosophy and graduating in 1994.\nAfter several years of developing his work in relative isolation he returned to art school and in 2001 he completed an MA in Fine Art at Wimbledon School of Art. He has worked for the past twenty years from a rural setting in his studio in Oxfordshire<ref>\"Eric Butcher: Richness in Rightness\", p.22. Paul Carey-Kent {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}.</ref> a converted barn and a place of tranquility, creativity and precision.<ref>Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, Collaborating Artists [https://www.patrickheide.com/index.php/artists/eric-butcher]</ref> \n\n==Career==\n===Early work===\nButcher's earliest exhibited works were compositions of oil, resin and spray paint on large, tablet-like MDF supports. The combination of painted surface and exaggerated depth of the support made the works deliberately and obviously three-dimensional objects \u2013 an \u2018attempt to deny the viewer the desire to see the surface as anything other than surface\u2019.<ref>(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.11. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> This composed physical presence was inherent in even the most restrained of Butcher's works, as William Packer would go on to say in his introduction to Butcher's 2005 catalogue, Carbon Candy, \u2018even when hung conventionally, flat to the wall, they remain obviously and directly physical\u2019.<ref>\u201dCarbon Candy\u201d, p.4. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}}.</ref> Although characterised by their appearance \u2013 an abstract \u2018accretion of paint, resin and various other fluids\u2019<ref name=\"Arcs\">(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.12. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> - their manufacture was faithful to the rules that govern Butcher's creative process.<ref>Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/statement/ \"statement\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> Butcher has said of his practice that \u2018the application or subtraction of paint as a set of processes is achieved through a variety of continually evolving techniques which draw attention to the physical properties of my materials\u2019,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\">Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/statement/\"statement\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> a result that would be most clearly manifest in his subsequent metal works. The introduction of metal as a support revolutionised Butcher's creative output and his approach to the act of painting, \u2018it may just be a flat piece of metal\u2026 But they all have little nicks, edges and imperfections\u2026 the end result is an accumulation of what I have learnt about that surface\u2019.<ref name=\"Arcs\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, ER.358.jpg|thumb|left|alt=ER.358.|ER.358 Oil and resin on extruded aluminium box sections.]]\n===Philosophy and approach to painting===\n\u2018The application or subtraction of paint\u2019 in Butcher's practice is executed through the use of \u2018a metal blade drawn across the painting\u2019s surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\">\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.7. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> pulling a thin transparent monochrome of oil and resin over the metal support, \u2018this procedure is then repeated and repeated, building up a surface of accumulated residues'.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> The outcome of each painting is determined by \u2018variations in colour modulation\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> and largely \u2018by the physical characteristics of the support\u2019.<ref>Eric Butcher [https://www.ericbutcher.com/statement\u201dstatement\u201d]</ref> 'Paint is registered in vertical and horizontal bands across the surface of the metal plane, with areas of metal left unpainted and its polished face exposed to the viewer. the colour is omitted and the bare aluminium emerges. As a result two rhythms arise; on the one hand the colour fields are interrupted by sections of contrasting colour, and on the other hand we have the various degrees of paint application, which range from impasto to diaphanous. They completely cover the aluminium, yet also let it shimmer through'.<ref>Kr\u00e4mer, Harald (2013). \"Bildwerke\", p.23. Galerie Robert Drees.</ref> \n\nAlthough Butcher has a uniform approach to each work,<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> they nevertheless differ vastly from one another as the artist may encounter subtle material differences in the surface of each extrusion; burrs in the metal itself or unexpected variations in the applied paint wash.<ref>Sheldon, Julie (2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.32. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> Almost every piece will seek to preserve some element of the metal as well, \u2018the aluminium asserts itself as the artwork\u2019s true substance\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> As Butcher seeks to articulate the surfaces of aluminium structures,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> he does so not only through the repetitive layers of colour application, but also through the preservation of the support's original condition (before his intervention) \u2013 both make for an overall representation of that particular structure's history.\n\nFor the Material Witness exhibition at Toomey Tourell gallery in 2010, Butcher exhibited fourteen of his painted aluminium extrusions.<ref name=\"Baker\">Baker, Kenneth (March 13, 2010). \u201cButcher Shines at Toomey Tourell\u201d. San Francisco Chronicle, p.E-1.</ref> Hung vertically and spaced asymmetrically with a measured and careful distance between one another,<ref name=\"Baker\" /> the display articulated Butcher's increasing awareness of, and preoccupation with, \u2018installation\u2019 in creating a total cohesive experience rather than an isolated object.<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> As Kenneth Baker, in his [[San Francisco Chronicle]] review, wrote of the work's interaction with the space it occupied, \u2018to walk this piece is to compose and recompose it through observation. Its geometry and built-in illusionism dictate that it cannot be seen whole\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> This can also be said of Butcher's curatorial practice, where, as in the Definite Article exhibition curated by the artist himself,<ref>\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.3. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> he deals with the scale and arrangement of works by Roger Ackling, [[Marc Vaux]] and Cathy Wade, as well as his own. Butcher's attempts within his own works in that exhibition to, \u2018engage the space around the painted surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> were similarly factors that he encountered in his curation of the exhibition as a whole, \u2018each of the artists\u2026 employs a range of techniques to encourage the viewer to engage with the work physically\u2019.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, GR.578.jpg|thumb|right|alt=GR.578.|GR.578 Blind embossed paper with cutouts.]]\n\n===Site-specific Installations===\nEric Butcher's site-specific installations are interventions in space. Like the intimate relationship between painted surface and objects that distinguish his work, they become 'a pause in the act or a mistake in the material'<ref name=Bildwerke>Kr\u00e4mer, Harald (2013). \"Bildwerke\", p.27. Galerie Robert Drees.</ref>, 'subtle and stunning, installed in space dispersed over corners, corridors or in staircases they become architecture in motion'.<ref name=TimeTrial16>Heide, Patrick (2019). 'Time Trial', p.16. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> This methodology can be seen in the lengths, or fragments, of aluminium that 'seem to cling to the wall [in his installations]. In part driven by chance, and yet still composed according to a strict order'.<ref name=Bildwerke /> The context of these installations have become increasingly important, 'determined by aspects of its context; both its physical environment and psychological purpose'<ref name=TimeTrial>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.89. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> as Butcher says in his recent catalogue, Time Trial. 'As soon as I started to consider the intersections between surfaces and the wall, I was naturally, logically led to a consideration of the whole environmental context of the work and hence to site-specificity.'<ref name=TimeTrial /> This mirrors his approach to the objects he works with, the 'relationship between the painted surface and the object (upon which one surface has been singled out for preferential treatment), between 'surface' and 'objectness'.<ref name=TimeTrial68>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.68. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> \n\nAlthough the components of these installations appear to 'cling to the wall'<ref name=Bildwerke />, the evidence of their fixings are increasingly integral to the installation, 'how a piece fixes to the wall, its method of construction, the way in which the work is joined together and adhered to its backing; I want this to be clear and evident. Bolts and fixings are used which in some cases pierce the painted surfaces'.<ref name=TimeTrial65>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.65. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref>\n\n===Paperworks===\nAs a consequence of this preoccupation with installation, some of Butcher's most recent pieces, his works on paper, experiment diagrammatically with possible arrangements for his large-scale installations of aluminium pieces, 'they repeat\nthe principle of the aluminium works in their own specific way'<ref name=Bildwerke /> introducing elements of chance.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\">\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 77. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> In these paper works, impressions of metal plates are embossed into sheets of saturated paper by running it through a printing press.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 80. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> Some sections of the plates\u2019 impressions are then highlighted by ink, whereas some sections are cut out altogether \u2013 some left purely as a trace.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\" /> 'These interventions take place separated from one another, yet may also intertwine. Through these perforations, the wall which is behind the deckle edged paper becomes a component of the work and takes on a bigger or smaller role depending on the size and quantity of perforations'.<ref name=Bildwerke /> Butcher refers to this register of trace in his paper works as speaking, metaphorically, of loss and absence.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 81. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref>\n\nShortly after the death of his father, Butcher created a series of works from gunpowder residue and clay on burnt paper. These found 'drawings' were from 'spent fireworks cartridges from a beach display [that] had been casually tossed into the sea'<ref name=richnessrightness>(2019).\"Eric Butcher: Richness in Rightness\" Carey-Kent, Paul, p.124. Galerie Robert Dress, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}</ref>. 'Eric started to gather them up for more suitable disposal. Then he became interested in how the spent energy had left its marks, especially as those traces were \u2013 in line with the aims of his wider practice \u2013 free from the subjectivity of creative decision making'.<ref name=richnessrightness /> Butcher states how 'the absence of something no longer present coupled with enormous pressure (in the case of the embossed pieces) or heat (in the case of the firework pieces) I find very suggestive and full of implications. On a metaphorical level they speak of loss and spent energy'.<ref>\"Time Trial\"(2019). Butcher, Eric, p.139. Galerie Robert Dress, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}</ref>\n\nIt is also apparent that the artist is re-evaluating his own resources in his use of paper, taking environmental concerns into the work itself. As he says in his recent Time Trial catalogue, '[in] trying to consume less, tread more lightly on the planet, it would be curiously contradictory not to impose the same logic of questioning on my work. Aluminium production is an energy intensive business, so I am increasingly using recycled and reused materials'.<ref>\"Time Trial\"(2019). Butcher, Eric, p.124. Galerie Robert Dress, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibition History==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Selected Solo Exhibitions !! Gallery/Museum\n|-\n| 2020 || Sweet Heresy || Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London\n|-\n| 2018 || Artificial Light || Nancy Toomey Fine Art, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2015 || Data Capture || Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London\n|-\n| 2013 || A Synthetic Kind of Love || Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany\n|-\n| 2010 || Material Witness || Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2007 || Honey Trap || Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2007 || Static Interference || Vertigo gallery, London\n|-\n| 2005 || Hanging Garden || Text + Work, the Art Institute at Bournemouth\n|-\n| 2005 || Arte Fiera || Vertigo gallery, Bologna, Italy\n|-\n| 2004 || Carbon Candy || Vertigo gallery, London \n|-\n| 2003 || Arcs + Surfaces || Vertigo gallery, London \n|-\n| 2002 || Cusp (two-person with Rebecca McLynn) || Sarah Myerscough Fine Art, London\n|-\n| 2000 || A Line of Enquiry || The Loading Bay, London\n|-\n| 1999 || The Antidote || The Loading Bay, London\n|-\n| 1997 || New Paintings || Concord Sylvania, London\n|-\n| 1997 || The Painted Figure (two-person with Gabriel Schmitz) || Hirschl Contemporary Art, London \n|-\n| 1995 || Lingering in Chambers of the Sea || The Acorn gallery, Liverpool\n|-\n| 1995 || New Paintings || Gallery 28, Reading\n|-\n| 1993 || Coming Up for Air || Engert Haus, Munich, Germany\n|-\n| 1991 || Beata Clarisa || Corpus Christi College, Cambridge\n|}\n\n=== Group Exhibitions ===\nEric Butcher has participated in many group shows including \"The Waterlilly Foundation\", [[Cambridge Guildhall]] (1994), \"The Genitals Are Beauty\", The House of William Blake, London (1995), \"The Art Experience\", The Atrium Gallery, London (1997), \"Wall to Wall\", Sarah Myerscough Fine Art, London (2002), \"Paperwork\" and \"30 x 30\", Vertigo Gallery, London (2003), \"Surface\", Vertigo Gallery (2004), the touring exhibition \"Definite Article\" with Roger Ackling, [[Marc Vaux]] and Cathy Wade, Vertigo gallery, London and Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2005/6), \"Meeting Place - Contemporary Art and the Museum Collection\", [[Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum]], Bournemouth and the Arts Institute at Bournemouth (curated by Stephanie James & Jackie Serafopoulos) (2007), \"Underground\", [[Shoreditch]] Town Hall basement, London (three-person with Roger Ackling and Sim\u00f3n Granell) (2007), \"Ten\", Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2008), \"\u00dcber Fl\u00e4chen\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2010), \"Raw\", Pertwee, Anderson & Gold, London, (2011), \"Beyond the Commission\", The Gallery, Arts University College Bournemouth (2011), \"One Thing Leads to Another\", Portland House, Malvern (2011), \"The Devil Finds Work for Idle Hands\", Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2012), \"ReGroup\", Red Space, London (2012).\n\nRecent selected group exhibitions also include the touring exhibition \"A Machine Aesthetic\", Gallery North [[Northumbria University]], Newcastle; The Gallery, AUB, Bournemouth; Project Space Plus, University of Lincoln; The Gallery, Norwich University of the Arts; Transition Gallery, London, \"Down to Zero\", Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London (curated by Michael Roberts), \"(Detail)\", H Project Space, Bangkok, Thailand; Usher Gallery, Lincoln; Transition gallery, London (curated by Andrew Bracey) (2014), \"An Einem Tisch - Contemporary Geometrical Abstraction\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany, \"Beyond Gravity II\", Galerie und Kunstcabinett Corona Unger, Bremen, Germany (2016), \"OVADA Seven Counties Open\", OVADA Warehouse, Oxford, \"The Jerwood Drawing Prize\", Jerwood Space, London, East Gallery, Norwich, The Edge, Bath, Sidney Cooper Gallery, Canterbury Vane Gallery, Newcastle-upon-Tyne, \"Mardi Gras Requiem\", Project Space Plus, Lincoln (2017), \"Intensity\", the House of St. Barnabas, London (curated by Paul Carey-Kent), \"Einsnullnull\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2018), \"Everything but Canvas\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2019), and \"Invited By\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2019/20).\n\n==Curating==\nButcher's creative practice has also embraced curating; initiating exhibitions/projects including Emission (2001), Definite Article (2005/6), Underground (2007), The Devil Finds Work for Idle Hands (2012) and A Machine Aesthetic (2013/14). A Machine Aesthetic (co-curated with Sim\u00f3n Granell), was a major national touring exhibition presenting the work of 11 contemporary British artists whose creative practices engaged with the concept of mechanisation. The exhibition explored the various manifestations, uses and influences of different aspects of mechanisation within the practices of an otherwise diverse group of artists (with [[Andrew Bracey]], Eric Butcher, David Connearn, Rob Currie, Paul Goodfellow, Sim\u00f3n Granell, [[Emma Hart (artist)]], Dan Hays, Natasha Kidd, Tim Knowles, Michael Roberts). In conjunction with the exhibition, the curators guest edited an edition of the arts and culture magazine Garageland (issue XVI: Machines)<ref>[https://www.transitiongallery.co.uk/htmlpages/editions/GL16/intro.htm \"Garageland: issue XVI: Machines\" {{ISSN|1749-9267}}.</ref>, which was themed to coincide with the show.\n\n\n==Further reading==\n*Butcher Shines at Toomey Tourell, Kenneth Baker, San Francisco Chronicle, pg. E - 1, March 13, 2010\n* Material Witness, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}. Text: Roy Exley, Eric Butcher & the Aluminium Works\n* Underground, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}. Texts: John Haldane, Underground; Lee Trimings, Loveslaves; Julie Sheldon, Process by Protocol; Tania Kovats, Digging.\n* Meeting Place, the Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum, Bournemouth, in association with Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, {{ISBN|978-0-901196-20-0}}, Ed. Stephanie James & Les Buckingham. Texts inc. Eric Butcher, Discoveries\n* Art at More London, The LG collection of Contemporary art, London (collection catalogue), Ed. Margaret O\u2019Regan\n* Hanging Garden, Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, Bournemouth {{ISBN|0-901196-09-6}} (exhibition catalogue). Text, James Barron, Spaces, In, Out and Around\n* Definite Article, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: Eric Butcher, Objects and Surfaces. Essay reprinted (abridged) in Art & Architecture Journal, No. 63, Autumn 2005\n* Carbon Candy, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: William Packer, Untitled\n* Arcs + Surfaces, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}} (exhibition catalogue). Texts: Angela Kingston, New Paintings by Eric Butcher, Catherine Shearn, A Conversation with Eric Butcher.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ericbutcher.com Eric Butcher website]\n*[http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ Eric Butcher at Toomey Tourell gallery]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher Eric Butcher at Galerie Robert Drees]\n*[https://www.patrickheide.com/artists/eric-butcher Eric Butcher at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butcher, Eric}}\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century English painters]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singaporean emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People associated with Arts University Bournemouth]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n\n| image         = File:Eric Butcher in his studio, photographed by Jonny Back.jpg\n| alt           =\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       = Eric Butcher in his studio\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1970}}\n| birth_place   = Singapore\n| nationality   = [[Great Britain|British]]\n| field         = Painting\n| training      = [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], \n[[Wimbledon College of Art|Wimbledon School of Art]]\n| movement      = [[Abstract art]]\n| works         =\n}}\n\n'''Eric Butcher''' (born 1970) is a contemporary British abstract painter known for his reductive, processed-based approach.\n\nButcher read philosophy at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], graduating in 1994 and completed an MA in Fine Art at [[Wimbledon College of Art|Wimbledon School of Art]] in 2001. He has exhibited extensively in the UK and internationally with shows in Germany, Italy, Australia and the USA.<ref name=\"Underground\">(2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.78. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> He currently shows with Toomey Tourell gallery, San Francisco,<ref>Toomey-Tourell Fine Art [http://toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ \"Eric Butcher\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001153714/http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher |date=2012-10-01 }}</ref> Galerie Robert Drees in Hannover<ref>Galerie Robert Drees [http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher |date=2012-08-23 }}\"Eric Butcher\"</ref> and Patrick Heide Contemporary Art.<ref>Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, Collaborating Artists [https://www.patrickheide.com/index.php/artists/eric-butcher]</ref> \n\nHe has received awards from the [[Arts Council England|Arts Council, England]] and the [[Arts and Humanities Research Council]]. He has also held an Arts Institute at Bournemouth Research Fellowship (now the [[Arts University Bournemouth|AUB]]<ref>[http://aub.ac.uk/about-us/governance/\u201dArts University College Bournemouth\u201d]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref>) and was the Centre for Arts International Research/Liverpool School of Art & Design Multiple Perspectives Fellow 2007.<ref name=\"Underground\" />\n\nButcher was a selected artist in the final Jerwood Drawing Prize in 2017<ref>Jerwood Drawing Prize 2017, published by the Jerwood Charitable Foundation, London {{ISBN|978-1-908331-29-8}} (texts: Anita Taylor, David Dibosa, Helen Legg, Michael Simpson)</ref> (now [[Trinity Buoy Wharf Drawing Prize]]) alongside artists such as [[Barbara Walker (artist)]] and selected by writer/curator, David Dibosa; director of [[Tate Liverpool]], Helen Legg (then director of [[Spike Island Artspace]]); and [[Michael Simpson (painter)]]. In 2020 Butcher exhibited his second solo show, Sweet Heresy<ref>Sweet Heresy | Eric Butcher [https://www.patrickheide.com/exhibitions/sweet-heresy-eric-butcher]</ref>, at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, which coincided with the release of Time Trial, a newly published 160-page hardback catalogue of his recent work.<ref>\u201dTime Trial\u201d, Eric Butcher {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}.</ref>\n\n\n__TOC__\n\n==Early Life and Education==\nEric Butcher was born in Singapore in 1970 to a Dutch mother and British father. Shortly after he was born the family moved to Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia and then settled in the UK in Hampshire, England in 1974.\nAfter leaving school at 16 he spent two formative years studying art at [[Basingstoke College of Technology]], after which he undertook A Levels at evening classes and eventually found his way to [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]], reading philosophy and graduating in 1994.\nAfter several years of developing his work in relative isolation he returned to art school and in 2001 he completed an MA in Fine Art at Wimbledon School of Art. He has worked for the past twenty years from a rural setting in his studio in Oxfordshire<ref>\"Eric Butcher: Richness in Rightness\", p.22. Paul Carey-Kent {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}.</ref> a converted barn and a place of tranquility, creativity and precision.<ref>Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, Collaborating Artists [https://www.patrickheide.com/index.php/artists/eric-butcher]</ref> \n\n==Career==\n===Early work===\nButcher's earliest exhibited works were compositions of oil, resin and spray paint on large, tablet-like MDF supports. The combination of painted surface and exaggerated depth of the support made the works deliberately and obviously three-dimensional objects \u2013 an \u2018attempt to deny the viewer the desire to see the surface as anything other than surface\u2019.<ref>(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.11. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> This composed physical presence was inherent in even the most restrained of Butcher's works, as William Packer would go on to say in his introduction to Butcher's 2005 catalogue, Carbon Candy, \u2018even when hung conventionally, flat to the wall, they remain obviously and directly physical\u2019.<ref>\u201dCarbon Candy\u201d, p.4. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}}.</ref> Although characterised by their appearance \u2013 an abstract \u2018accretion of paint, resin and various other fluids\u2019<ref name=\"Arcs\">(2003). \u201cArcs + Surfaces, A Conversation with Eric Butcher\u201d, p.12. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}}.</ref> - their manufacture was faithful to the rules that govern Butcher's creative process.<ref>Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/statement/ \"statement\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> Butcher has said of his practice that \u2018the application or subtraction of paint as a set of processes is achieved through a variety of continually evolving techniques which draw attention to the physical properties of my materials\u2019,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\">Eric Butcher [http://www.ericbutcher.com/statement/\"statement\u201d] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824131126/http://ericbutcher.com/statement/ |date=2013-08-24 }}.</ref> a result that would be most clearly manifest in his subsequent metal works. The introduction of metal as a support revolutionised Butcher's creative output and his approach to the act of painting, \u2018it may just be a flat piece of metal\u2026 But they all have little nicks, edges and imperfections\u2026 the end result is an accumulation of what I have learnt about that surface\u2019.<ref name=\"Arcs\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, ER.358.jpg|thumb|left|alt=ER.358.|ER.358 Oil and resin on extruded aluminium box sections.]]\n===Philosophy and approach to painting===\n\u2018The application or subtraction of paint\u2019 in Butcher's practice is executed through the use of \u2018a metal blade drawn across the painting\u2019s surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\">\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.7. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> pulling a thin transparent monochrome of oil and resin over the metal support, \u2018this procedure is then repeated and repeated, building up a surface of accumulated residues'.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> The outcome of each painting is determined by \u2018variations in colour modulation\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> and largely \u2018by the physical characteristics of the support\u2019.<ref>Eric Butcher [https://www.ericbutcher.com/statement\u201dstatement\u201d]</ref> 'Paint is registered in vertical and horizontal bands across the surface of the metal plane, with areas of metal left unpainted and its polished face exposed to the viewer. the colour is omitted and the bare aluminium emerges. As a result two rhythms arise; on the one hand the colour fields are interrupted by sections of contrasting colour, and on the other hand we have the various degrees of paint application, which range from impasto to diaphanous. They completely cover the aluminium, yet also let it shimmer through'.<ref>Kr\u00e4mer, Harald (2013). \"Bildwerke\", p.23. Galerie Robert Drees.</ref> \n\nAlthough Butcher has a uniform approach to each work,<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> they nevertheless differ vastly from one another as the artist may encounter subtle material differences in the surface of each extrusion; burrs in the metal itself or unexpected variations in the applied paint wash.<ref>Sheldon, Julie (2007). \u201cUnderground\u201d, p.32. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}.</ref> Almost every piece will seek to preserve some element of the metal as well, \u2018the aluminium asserts itself as the artwork\u2019s true substance\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> As Butcher seeks to articulate the surfaces of aluminium structures,<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> he does so not only through the repetitive layers of colour application, but also through the preservation of the support's original condition (before his intervention) \u2013 both make for an overall representation of that particular structure's history.\n\nFor the Material Witness exhibition at Toomey Tourell gallery in 2010, Butcher exhibited fourteen of his painted aluminium extrusions.<ref name=\"Baker\">Baker, Kenneth (March 13, 2010). \u201cButcher Shines at Toomey Tourell\u201d. San Francisco Chronicle, p.E-1.</ref> Hung vertically and spaced asymmetrically with a measured and careful distance between one another,<ref name=\"Baker\" /> the display articulated Butcher's increasing awareness of, and preoccupation with, \u2018installation\u2019 in creating a total cohesive experience rather than an isolated object.<ref name=\"ericbutcher\" /> As Kenneth Baker, in his [[San Francisco Chronicle]] review, wrote of the work's interaction with the space it occupied, \u2018to walk this piece is to compose and recompose it through observation. Its geometry and built-in illusionism dictate that it cannot be seen whole\u2019.<ref name=\"Baker\" /> This can also be said of Butcher's curatorial practice, where, as in the Definite Article exhibition curated by the artist himself,<ref>\u201dDefinite Article, Objects and Surfaces, Eric Butcher\u201d, p.3. Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}}.</ref> he deals with the scale and arrangement of works by Roger Ackling, [[Marc Vaux]] and Cathy Wade, as well as his own. Butcher's attempts within his own works in that exhibition to, \u2018engage the space around the painted surface\u2019<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" /> were similarly factors that he encountered in his curation of the exhibition as a whole, \u2018each of the artists\u2026 employs a range of techniques to encourage the viewer to engage with the work physically\u2019.<ref name=\"DefiniteArticle\" />\n[[File:Eric Butcher, GR.578.jpg|thumb|right|alt=GR.578.|GR.578 Blind embossed paper with cutouts.]]\n\n===Site-specific Installations===\nEric Butcher's site-specific installations are interventions in space. Like the intimate relationship between painted surface and objects that distinguish his work, they become 'a pause in the act or a mistake in the material'<ref name=Bildwerke>Kr\u00e4mer, Harald (2013). \"Bildwerke\", p.27. Galerie Robert Drees.</ref>, 'subtle and stunning, installed in space dispersed over corners, corridors or in staircases they become architecture in motion'.<ref name=TimeTrial16>Heide, Patrick (2019). 'Time Trial', p.16. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> This methodology can be seen in the lengths, or fragments, of aluminium that 'seem to cling to the wall [in his installations]. In part driven by chance, and yet still composed according to a strict order'.<ref name=Bildwerke /> The context of these installations have become increasingly important, 'determined by aspects of its context; both its physical environment and psychological purpose'<ref name=TimeTrial>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.89. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> as Butcher says in his recent catalogue, Time Trial. 'As soon as I started to consider the intersections between surfaces and the wall, I was naturally, logically led to a consideration of the whole environmental context of the work and hence to site-specificity.'<ref name=TimeTrial /> This mirrors his approach to the objects he works with, the 'relationship between the painted surface and the object (upon which one surface has been singled out for preferential treatment), between 'surface' and 'objectness'.<ref name=TimeTrial68>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.68. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref> \n\nAlthough the components of these installations appear to 'cling to the wall'<ref name=Bildwerke />, the evidence of their fixings are increasingly integral to the installation, 'how a piece fixes to the wall, its method of construction, the way in which the work is joined together and adhered to its backing; I want this to be clear and evident. Bolts and fixings are used which in some cases pierce the painted surfaces'.<ref name=TimeTrial65>Butcher, Eric (2019). 'Time Trial', p.65. Galerie Robert Drees, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art and Eric Butcher.</ref>\n\n===Paperworks===\nAs a consequence of this preoccupation with installation, some of Butcher's most recent pieces, his works on paper, experiment diagrammatically with possible arrangements for his large-scale installations of aluminium pieces, 'they repeat\nthe principle of the aluminium works in their own specific way'<ref name=Bildwerke /> introducing elements of chance.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\">\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 77. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> In these paper works, impressions of metal plates are embossed into sheets of saturated paper by running it through a printing press.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 80. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref> Some sections of the plates\u2019 impressions are then highlighted by ink, whereas some sections are cut out altogether \u2013 some left purely as a trace.<ref name=\"ConversationWith\" /> 'These interventions take place separated from one another, yet may also intertwine. Through these perforations, the wall which is behind the deckle edged paper becomes a component of the work and takes on a bigger or smaller role depending on the size and quantity of perforations'.<ref name=Bildwerke /> Butcher refers to this register of trace in his paper works as speaking, metaphorically, of loss and absence.<ref>\u201dA Conversation With Jagjit Chuhan\u201d, p. 81. Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}.</ref>\n\nShortly after the death of his father, Butcher created a series of works from gunpowder residue and clay on burnt paper. These found 'drawings' were from 'spent fireworks cartridges from a beach display [that] had been casually tossed into the sea'<ref name=richnessrightness>(2019).\"Eric Butcher: Richness in Rightness\" Carey-Kent, Paul, p.124. Galerie Robert Dress, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}</ref>. 'Eric started to gather them up for more suitable disposal. Then he became interested in how the spent energy had left its marks, especially as those traces were \u2013 in line with the aims of his wider practice \u2013 free from the subjectivity of creative decision making'.<ref name=richnessrightness /> \n\nIt is also apparent that the artist is re-evaluating his own resources in his use of paper, taking environmental concerns into the work itself. As he says in his recent Time Trial catalogue, '[in] trying to consume less, tread more lightly on the planet, it would be curiously contradictory not to impose the same logic of questioning on my work. Aluminium production is an energy intensive business, so I am increasingly using recycled and reused materials'.<ref>\"Time Trial\", Butcher, Eric, p.124. Galerie Robert Dress, Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, {{ISBN|978-1-5272-5156-4}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibition History==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Selected Solo Exhibitions !! Gallery/Museum\n|-\n| 2020 || Sweet Heresy || Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London\n|-\n| 2018 || Artificial Light || Nancy Toomey Fine Art, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2015 || Data Capture || Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London\n|-\n| 2013 || A Synthetic Kind of Love || Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany\n|-\n| 2010 || Material Witness || Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2007 || Honey Trap || Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA\n|-\n| 2007 || Static Interference || Vertigo gallery, London\n|-\n| 2005 || Hanging Garden || Text + Work, the Art Institute at Bournemouth\n|-\n| 2005 || Arte Fiera || Vertigo gallery, Bologna, Italy\n|-\n| 2004 || Carbon Candy || Vertigo gallery, London \n|-\n| 2003 || Arcs + Surfaces || Vertigo gallery, London \n|-\n| 2002 || Cusp (two-person with Rebecca McLynn) || Sarah Myerscough Fine Art, London\n|-\n| 2000 || A Line of Enquiry || The Loading Bay, London\n|-\n| 1999 || The Antidote || The Loading Bay, London\n|-\n| 1997 || New Paintings || Concord Sylvania, London\n|-\n| 1997 || The Painted Figure (two-person with Gabriel Schmitz) || Hirschl Contemporary Art, London \n|-\n| 1995 || Lingering in Chambers of the Sea || The Acorn gallery, Liverpool\n|-\n| 1995 || New Paintings || Gallery 28, Reading\n|-\n| 1993 || Coming Up for Air || Engert Haus, Munich, Germany\n|-\n| 1991 || Beata Clarisa || Corpus Christi College, Cambridge\n|}\n\n=== Group Exhibitions ===\nEric Butcher has participated in many group shows including \"The Waterlilly Foundation\", [[Cambridge Guildhall]] (1994), \"The Genitals Are Beauty\", The House of William Blake, London (1995), \"The Art Experience\", The Atrium Gallery, London (1997), \"Wall to Wall\", Sarah Myerscough Fine Art, London (2002), \"Paperwork\" and \"30 x 30\", Vertigo Gallery, London (2003), \"Surface\", Vertigo Gallery (2004), the touring exhibition \"Definite Article\" with Roger Ackling, [[Marc Vaux]] and Cathy Wade, Vertigo gallery, London and Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2005/6), \"Meeting Place - Contemporary Art and the Museum Collection\", [[Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum]], Bournemouth and the Arts Institute at Bournemouth (curated by Stephanie James & Jackie Serafopoulos) (2007), \"Underground\", [[Shoreditch]] Town Hall basement, London (three-person with Roger Ackling and Sim\u00f3n Granell) (2007), \"Ten\", Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2008), \"\u00dcber Fl\u00e4chen\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2010), \"Raw\", Pertwee, Anderson & Gold, London, (2011), \"Beyond the Commission\", The Gallery, Arts University College Bournemouth (2011), \"One Thing Leads to Another\", Portland House, Malvern (2011), \"The Devil Finds Work for Idle Hands\", Toomey-Tourell gallery, San Francisco, USA (2012), \"ReGroup\", Red Space, London (2012).\n\nRecent selected group exhibitions also include the touring exhibition \"A Machine Aesthetic\", Gallery North [[Northumbria University]], Newcastle; The Gallery, AUB, Bournemouth; Project Space Plus, University of Lincoln; The Gallery, Norwich University of the Arts; Transition Gallery, London, \"Down to Zero\", Patrick Heide Contemporary Art, London (curated by Michael Roberts), \"(Detail)\", H Project Space, Bangkok, Thailand; Usher Gallery, Lincoln; Transition gallery, London (curated by Andrew Bracey) (2014), \"An Einem Tisch - Contemporary Geometrical Abstraction\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany, \"Beyond Gravity II\", Galerie und Kunstcabinett Corona Unger, Bremen, Germany (2016), \"OVADA Seven Counties Open\", OVADA Warehouse, Oxford, \"The Jerwood Drawing Prize\", Jerwood Space, London, East Gallery, Norwich, The Edge, Bath, Sidney Cooper Gallery, Canterbury Vane Gallery, Newcastle-upon-Tyne, \"Mardi Gras Requiem\", Project Space Plus, Lincoln (2017), \"Intensity\", the House of St. Barnabas, London (curated by Paul Carey-Kent), \"Einsnullnull\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2018), \"Everything but Canvas\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2019), and \"Invited By\", Galerie Robert Drees, Hannover, Germany (2019/20).\n\n==Curating==\nButcher's creative practice has also embraced curating; initiating exhibitions/projects including Emission (2001), Definite Article (2005/6), Underground (2007), The Devil Finds Work for Idle Hands (2012) and A Machine Aesthetic (2013/14). A Machine Aesthetic (co-curated with Sim\u00f3n Granell), was a major national touring exhibition presenting the work of 11 contemporary British artists whose creative practices engaged with the concept of mechanisation. The exhibition explored the various manifestations, uses and influences of different aspects of mechanisation within the practices of an otherwise diverse group of artists (with [[Andrew Bracey]], Eric Butcher, David Connearn, Rob Currie, Paul Goodfellow, Sim\u00f3n Granell, [[Emma Hart (artist)]], Dan Hays, Natasha Kidd, Tim Knowles, Michael Roberts). In conjunction with the exhibition, the curators guest edited an edition of the arts and culture magazine Garageland (issue XVI: Machines)<ref>[https://www.transitiongallery.co.uk/htmlpages/editions/GL16/intro.htm \"Garageland: issue XVI: Machines\" {{ISSN|1749-9267}}.</ref>, which was themed to coincide with the show.\n\n\n==Further reading==\n*Butcher Shines at Toomey Tourell, Kenneth Baker, San Francisco Chronicle, pg. E - 1, March 13, 2010\n* Material Witness, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9557360-4-9}}. Text: Roy Exley, Eric Butcher & the Aluminium Works\n* Underground, Centre for Art International Research, Liverpool, {{ISBN|978-0-9552820-6-5}}. Texts: John Haldane, Underground; Lee Trimings, Loveslaves; Julie Sheldon, Process by Protocol; Tania Kovats, Digging.\n* Meeting Place, the Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum, Bournemouth, in association with Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, {{ISBN|978-0-901196-20-0}}, Ed. Stephanie James & Les Buckingham. Texts inc. Eric Butcher, Discoveries\n* Art at More London, The LG collection of Contemporary art, London (collection catalogue), Ed. Margaret O\u2019Regan\n* Hanging Garden, Text + Work, the Arts Institute at Bournemouth, Bournemouth {{ISBN|0-901196-09-6}} (exhibition catalogue). Text, James Barron, Spaces, In, Out and Around\n* Definite Article, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-13-7}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: Eric Butcher, Objects and Surfaces. Essay reprinted (abridged) in Art & Architecture Journal, No. 63, Autumn 2005\n* Carbon Candy, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-12-9}} (exhibition catalogue). Text: William Packer, Untitled\n* Arcs + Surfaces, Vertigo Gallery, London, {{ISBN|1-903771-08-0}} (exhibition catalogue). Texts: Angela Kingston, New Paintings by Eric Butcher, Catherine Shearn, A Conversation with Eric Butcher.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ericbutcher.com Eric Butcher website]\n*[http://www.toomey-tourell.com/artists/eric-butcher/ Eric Butcher at Toomey Tourell gallery]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120823232622/http://www.galerie-robert-drees.de/index.php/drees/kuenstler/eric_butcher Eric Butcher at Galerie Robert Drees]\n*[https://www.patrickheide.com/artists/eric-butcher Eric Butcher at Patrick Heide Contemporary Art]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butcher, Eric}}\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century English painters]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singaporean emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People associated with Arts University Bournemouth]]\n", "name_user": "Barrettjonathan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePaperworks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Butcher"}
